<DOC><DOCNO> AP881031-0127 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-31-88 1316EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Bulgaria-Emissions     10-31 0133</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Bulgaria-Emissions,0136</SECOND><HEAD>12 Countries Sign Declaration To Reduce Nitrogen Oxide</HEAD><DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Twelve countries Monday signed adeclaration to reduce emissions of air pollutants that contributeto acid rain and the depletion of the ozone layer.   The countries that promised to reduce by 30 percent theiremissions of nitrogen oxide in the next 10 years are Finland,Norway, Belgium, Italy, France, Austria, Switzerland, Sweden, WestGermany, Liechtenstein, Denmark and the Netherlands.   Nitrogen oxide, derived mostly from car exhaust fumes and theburning of fossil fuels, contributes to smog, acid rain and the``greenhouse effect,'' or the warming of the atmosphere aroundEarth.   The 12 members of the United Nations Economic Commission forEurope were in Sofia for a meeting of the Convention on Long-rangeTransboundary Air Pollution that begins Tuesday.</TEXT></DOC>